ожения. Сразу за островом находится материк. Маяк на острове светит даже днём, лишая возможности произносить то, что происходит на крите, а также существование самого маяка, чтобы не прознал Безымянный. К огню добавляет субстанцию каждые тысячный критянин, чтобы горело. Первый костер был такого размера, что всем на острове его было видно. Тогда и забыли бога, давшему Криту атрефакты. Можно маяк безнаказанно обогнуть, но никто не хочет этого делать.",536880055]],["^15",[3144,"^O","^1;",536880055]],["^15",[3144,"^F",3145,536880055]],["^15",[3144,"^X",73,536880055]],["^15",[3144,"^V",3147,536880055]],["^15",[3144,"^U",73,536880055]],["^15",[3144,"^;","~u68a60b9e-e4cf-432b-a480-cf9f58fd8a37",536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^Q","Цензура не всегда следует первому неудобному слову, иногда она его упреждает и сама есть первое слово.",536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^O","^1;",536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^F",3147,536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^X",73,536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^V",3147,536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^U",73,536880055]],["^15",[3145,"^;","~u68a60b9e-12d2-4dbf-b8dd-fef46c424f8e",536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^M",true,536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^Q","Эры\ncollapsed:: true",536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^O","^1;",536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^F",3147,536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^X",73,536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^V",2676,536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^U",73,536880055]],["^15",[3146,"^?",["^ "],536880489]],["^15",[3146,"^J",[],536880489]],["^15",[3146,"^4",["^ "],536880489]],["^15",[3146,"^;","~u68a60b9e-8da1-4f9a-9f0f-f3a626d25d58",536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^Q","Сначала было слово. Нет, сначала была немая истина.",536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^O","^1;",536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^F",2676,536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^X",73,536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^V",2676,536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^U",73,536880055]],["^15",[3147,"^;","~u68a60b9e-5165-4eac-b1b3-64f66fe45814",536880055]],["^15",[3149,"^Q","[[Свобода невыбора]]",536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^O","^1;",536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^F",2698,536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^X",2693,536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^V",2696,536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^U",2513,536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^U",2693,536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^H",2513,536880058]],["^15",[3149,"^;","~u68a60b9f-f6dd-49af-b64d-370a7adfc144",536880058]],["^15",[3150,"^K",1755712415749,536880061]],["^15",[3150,"^@",false,536880061]],["^15",[3150,"^Y","koan",536880061]],["^15",[3150,"^11","koan",536880061]],["^15",[3150,"^B",1755712415749,536880061]],["^15",[3150,"^;","~u68a60b9f-9a00-4404-ae53-6b6e9fd9de1d",536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^Q","#koan Пьеса в виде лингвистических и психологических коанов о герое с повествованиями с патологической обстоятельностью.",536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^O","^1;",536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^F",2710,536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^X",2709,536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^V",2709,536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^U",2709,536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^U",3150,536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^H",3150,536880061]],["^15",[3151,"^;","~u68a60b9f-8dad-4d69-8554-5e195af133b1",536880061]],["^15",[3153,"^3","tags:: [[Grozny Quiz]]\nplayed:: no\n\n- Что описывают четыре следующих слова на чеченском языке: ӀаьржбӀаьрг, жӀар, цӀентӀадам, биъса?\n\t- Масти игральных карт\n- На разных языках она называется из-за внешнего вида башней или замком, а из-за манеры движения кораблем, пушкой или колесницей. Как она называется на русском?\n\t- Ладья. Прим.: шахматная фигура.\n- Среди недостатков этой традиции - лишняя арифметика и дискриминация по внешнему виду.\n\t- Чаевые",536884253]],["^15",[3153,"^17","~m1757369130375",536884252]],["^15",[3153,"^Z","journals/2025_08_20.md",536880065]],["^15",[3154,"^Q","",536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^O","^1;",536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^@",false,536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^F",23,536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^X",23,536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^V",23,536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^U",23,536880072]],["^15",[3154,"^?",["^ "],536880071]],["^15",[3154,"^;","~u68a60bbd-bf15-475f-90c3-738d8615a779",536880071]],["^15",[3155,"^Q","Что описывают четыре следующих слова на чеченском языке: ӀаьржбӀаьрг, жӀар, цӀентӀадам, биъса?",536881259]],["^15",[3155,"^O","^1;",536880084]],["^15",[3155,"^@",true,536880084]],["^15",[3155,"^F",3049,536880084]],["^15",[3155,"^X",3048,536880084]],["^15",[3155,"^V",3048,536880084]],["^15",[3155,"^U",3048,536880085]],["^15",[3155,"^?",["^ "],536881259]],["^15",[3155,"^;","~u68a60bcf-3f67-4422-84a9-988f7589a7bb",536880084]],["^15",[3156,"^Q","Масти игральных карт",536881088]],["^15",[3156,"^O","^1;",536880239]],["^15",[3156,"^@",true,536880239]],["^15",[3156,"^F",3155,536880239]],["^15",[3156,"^X",3048,536880239]],["^15",[3156,"^V",3155,536880241]],["^15",[3156,"^U",3048,536881260]],["^15",[3156,"^?",["^ "],536881088]],["^15",[3156,"^;","~u68a60e81-e0c5-4632-81cf-39e6db827caf",536880239]],["^15",[3157,"^Q","Бонсай-раса",536880301]],["^15",[3157,"^O","^1;",536880253]],["^15",[3157,"^F",2517,536880253]],["^15",[3157,"^X",2516,536880253]],["^15",[3157,"^V",2516,536880253]],["^15",[3157,"^U",2516,536880254]],["^15",[3157,"^?",["^ "],536880301]],["^15",[3157,"^;","~u68a60eb9-4495-4c82-8f87-f749af10bddb",536880253]],["^15",[3158,"^Q","[[chess]]",536880317]],["^15",[3158,"^O","^1;",536880305]],["^15",[3158,"^F",1011,536880313]],["^15",[3158,"^X",999,536880305]],["^15",[3158,"^V",1015,536880313]],["^15",[3158,"^U",999,536880318]],["^15",[3158,"^U",2824,536880318]],["^15",[3158,"^?",["^ "],536880317]],["^15",[3158,"^H",2824,536880317]],["^15",[3158,"^;","~u68a60f61-f9e6-4ab3-a9d5-2827361e96ac",536880305]],["^15",[3162,"^K",1755716311633,536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^[",3164,536880366]],["^15",[3162,"^O","^1;",536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^@",false,536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^Y","hls__style_ an anti-textbook - lanham, richard",536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^11","hls__Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard",536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^?",["^ ","^26","[Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf](../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf)","^27","../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf"],536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^B",1755716311633,536880364]],["^15",[3162,"^;","~u68a61ad7-819b-4594-b736-e798410605a4",536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^Q","file:: [Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf](../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf)\nfile-path:: ../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf",536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^O","^1;",536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^F",3162,536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^X",3162,536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^V",3162,536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^U",2253,536880365]],["^15",[3163,"^U",2254,536880365]],["^15",[3163,"^U",3162,536880365]],["^15",[3163,"^:",true,536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^?",["^ ","^26","[Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf](../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf)","^27","../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf"],536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^J",["^14",["^26","^27"]],536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^H",2253,536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^H",2254,536880364]],["^15",[3163,"^;","~u68a61ad7-d823-4328-9a6c-9b9cc4288d2f",536880364]],["^15",[3164,"^3","file:: [Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf](../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf)\nfile-path:: ../assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.pdf\n\n- Goethe, in his conversations with Eckermann, is reputed to have said that “if any man would write in a noble style let him ﬁrst possess a noble soul.” Wonderful, but not much help. It may be, though some wise men have denied it, that virtue can be taught, but it seems unlikely that it can be taught in Freshman Composition. Nor sincerity. Nor spontaneity. Nor true grit. What can be taught is words. And they must be taught in the full matrix of human utterance, written and spoken, accompanied by a theory of style equally broad. A student bright enough to be taught style needs a context for it beyond didactic precept, an intelligible and sound context. Style cannot be taught only by lists of self-contradicting proverbs, strings of dos and don’ts. Students so instructed are not being taught; they are being housebroken. I recommend, in what follows, a particular strategy for a particular time and place. Prose style cannot be taught, as it has been, in—and as—a vacuum. It will simply end up, as has been happening with increasing frequency (vacuums being hard to teach), not being taught at all. It cannot be taught as a duty, for you cannot teach as duty what society does not feel a duty. Style must be taught for and as what it is—a pleasure, a grace, a joy, a\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 28\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68a61cff-f2d0-46dd-9774-939a8f516d96\n- delight. Pleasure will not, it is true, teach the dumb to speak, the stupid to write, or the bad to practice goodness. But neither will anything else.\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 29\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68a61d10-fe10-4ad4-8f74-a2a6c4643eff\n- The old Oscar Wilde jibe, “How do I know what I think until I hear what I say?” is literally true. Even purely expository prose less describes a truth than reveals one\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 48\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68a9f5ec-f0cb-4fc8-81aa-8848ebd7fe7f\n- We often observe this contrast between the absence of nominal inﬂection and the richness of the verbal inﬂection. This is due to the nature of the noun and the verb. The noun indicates an idea of permanent nature: a thing, a person, or a quality; the verb indicates a process. . . . For the very reason that it indicates a permanent notion, the noun has a sole form or at most a principal form from which the others are derived. On the other hand, the verb, which indicates a process, has personal forms and the expression of nuances which vary with languages, but can be numerous. The fact that the forms of the noun and verb obey divergent tendencies thus results from the nature of things. (A. Meillet, The Comparative Method in Historical Linguistics, p. 114)\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 83\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68b30a01-3afd-48ad-bc90-dc9f75b20277\n- the rhythm of a passage does not simply exist, as does its imagery: reading has to create it.\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 109\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68bb30e1-b05a-48f2-824e-2f0d47609504\n- Students of meter often refer to the tension between natural word stress and the stress pattern that meter imposes. In prose rhythm an analogous tension waits there for the exploiting. The reader must supply meaning, color it to a degree that poetry seldom permits. Because of this larger freedom, prose is often more fun to read aloud than poetry.\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 110\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68bb31ec-e84c-42a1-9ac3-17bc77e2e3b9\n- Syntax follows sense, either a pattern of association, or of subject, or as here, a chronological sequence. What follows builds upon what went before, modiﬁes it, restates it. A diachronic style, we might call it, one that acknowledges the passage of time. It often creates immediacy and action\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 117\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68bc6115-34ea-459d-b7b9-dae6a22533c4\n- The periodic style works diﬀerently. It encloses time into a single, syntactically controllable unit, treats experience synchronically rather than diachronically. Here, arrangement controls, not time. In it, order triumphs; in the running style, order operates. The running style surprises the mind operating; in the periodic style, the mind has ﬁnished its work.\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 118\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68bc614b-ff61-4f1f-880d-72ffa1b3808a\n- The periodic style, then, may represent pattern, and the running style, process.\n  ls-type:: annotation\n  hl-page:: 119\n  hl-color:: yellow\n  id:: 68bc635f-c0c3-4a12-9829-54d2c9081cc6",536883668]],["^15",[3164,"^17","~m1757176675571",536883672]],["^15",[3164,"^Z","pages/hls__Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.md",536880366]],["^15",[3165,"^3","{:highlights []}",536880370]],["^15",[3165,"^17","~m1755716311908",536880369]],["^15",[3165,"^Z","assets/Style_ An Anti-Textbook - Lanham, Richard.edn",536880369]],["^15",[3166,"^Q","Goethe, in his conversations with Eckermann, is reputed to have said that “if any man would write in a noble style let him ﬁrst possess a noble soul.” Wonderful, but not much help. It may be, though some wise men have denied it, that virtue can be taught, but it seems unlikely that it can be taught in Freshman Composition. Nor sincerity. Nor spontaneity. Nor true grit. What can be taught is words. And they must be taught in the full matrix of human utterance, written and spoken, accompanied by a theory of style equally broad. A student bright enough to be taught style needs a context for it beyond didactic precept, an intelligible and sound context. Style cannot be taught only by lists of self-contradicting proverbs, strings of dos and don’ts. Students so instructed are not being taught; they are being housebroken. I recommend, in what follows, a particular strategy for a particular time and place. Prose style cannot be taught, as it has been, in—and as—a vacuum. It will simply end up, as has been happening with increasing frequency (vacuums being hard to teach), not being taught at all. It cannot be taught as a duty, for you cannot teach as duty what society does not feel a duty. Style must be taught for and as what it is—a pleasure, a grace, a joy, a\nls-type:: annotation\nhl-page:: 28\nhl-color:: yellow\nid:: 68a61cff-f2d0-46dd-9774-939a8f516d96",536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^O","^1;",536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^@",false,536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^F",3163,536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^X",3162,536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^V",3162,536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^U",3162,536880384]],["^15",[3166,"^?",["^ ","^1Y","annotation","^1Z",28,"^1[","yellow","^1D","68a61cff-f2d0-46dd-9774-939a8f516d96"],536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^J",["^14",["^1Y","^1Z","^1[","^1D"]],536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^4",["^ ","^1Y","annotation","^1Z","28","^1[","yellow","^1D","68a61cff-f2d0-46dd-9774-939a8f516d96"],536880383]],["^15",[3166,"^;","~u68a61cff-f2d0-46dd-9774-939a8f516d96",536880383]],["^15",[3167,"^Q","delight. Pleasure will not, it is true, teach the dumb to speak, the stupid to write, or the bad to practice goodness. But neither will anything else.\nls-type:: annotation\nhl-page:: 29\nhl-color:: yellow\nid:: 68a61d10-fe10-4ad4-8f74-a2a6c4643eff",536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^O","^1;",536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^@",false,536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^F",3166,536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^X",3162,536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^V",3162,536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^U",3162,536880391]],["^15",[3167,"^?",["^ ","^1Y","annotation","^1Z",29,"^1[","yellow","^1D","68a61d10-fe10-4ad4-8f74-a2a6c4643eff"],536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^J",["^14",["^1Y","^1Z","^1[","^1D"]],536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^4",["^ ","^1Y","annotation","^1Z","29","^1[","yellow","^1D","68a61d10-fe10-4ad4-8f74-a2a6c4643eff"],536880390]],["^15",[3167,"^;","~u68a61d10-fe10-4ad4-8f74-a2a6c4643eff",536880390]],["^15",[3170,"^12",2,536880483]],["^15",[3173,"^Q","#+BEGIN_QUOTE\nПосвящается тем, кто пишет историю моей жизни: маме и сестре.\n#+END_QUOTE",536880489]],["^15",[3173,"^O","^1;",536880489]],["^15",[3173,"^F",2580,536880489]],["^15",[3173,"^X",73,536880489]],["^15",[3173,"^V",73,536880489]],["^15",[3173,"^U",73,536880489]],["^15",[3173,"^;","~u68a9f563-f695-46cf-95d3-fcf0d69666e3",536880489]],["^15",[3174,"^Q","The old Oscar Wilde jibe, “How do I know what I think until I hear what I say?” is literally true. Even purely expository prose less describes a truth than reveals one\nls-type:: annotation\nhl-page:: 48\nhl-color:: yellow\nid:: 68a9f5ec-f0cb-4fc8-81aa-8848ebd7fe7f",536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^O","^1;",536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^@",false,536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^F",3167,536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^X",3162,536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^V",3162,536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^U",3162,536880503]],["^15",[3174,"^?",["^ ","^1Y","annotation","^1Z",48,"^1[","yellow","^1D","68a9f5ec-f0cb-4fc8-81aa-8848ebd7fe7f"],536880502]],["^15",[3174,"^J",["^14",["^1Y","^1Z","^1